      "created_at": "2026-05-20T10:33:09Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-05-20T10:33:09Z",
      "author_association": "NONE",
      "body": "I have a machine-checked correctness proof of `secp256k1_scalar_mul`, the modular scalar multiplication over the group order N. It proves r = a * b mod N for all representable inputs, along with integer-overflow freeness in every intermediate and memory safety.\n\nIt covers both phases: the schoolbook 4x4-limb multiply producing the 512-bit product (`secp256k1_scalar_mul_512`) and the three-stage folding reduction (`secp256k1_scalar_reduce_512`, using the complement C = 2^256 - N plus a final conditional subtraction). I verified the non-assembly 64-bit path with VST 2.16. Since CompCert has no `__int128`, the 128-bit arithmetic uses the upstream two-limb struct fallback, so the verified code stays CompCert-compatible and the guarantee extends to assembly. It is roughly 300 lines of C against about 6,400 lines of proof, a 21:1 ratio.\n\nCode: https://github.com/remix7531/secp256k1-scalar-fv-test\nWrite-up: https://remix7531.com/post/formal_verification_secp256k1_scalar_mul/",
